issue.body:
These commands spawn a pod to run a `tcpdump` command and reports a failure if the output doesn't contain an expected string. We should also report the pod output in case the `tcpdump` command fails.

For the `inter-cluster` command, the `tcpdump` output is piped to `grep` to match the expected client message and stop when found. However if an error occurs then the message isn't matched and therefore the pod output is empty which isn't useful. Use `sed` instead of `grep` which also outputs the non-matching lines.

commits.message:
Improve error reporting for failed network pods (#432)

If the pod isn't scheduled, capture the reason and the pod status rather
than vaguely reporting that it timed out.

Signed-off-by: Tom Pantelis <tompantelis@gmail.com>

Give more permission for the diagnode pods

Some containers which run os like rhel/fedora runs tcpdump
as specific user id "72". So it needs pods to be privileged.
Also setting the runAsUser prevent the pods from starting with
random user id

* Make the diagnose pod a privileged
* Run the diagnose pod with userId 0

Signed-off-by: Aswin Suryanarayanan <aswinsuryan@gmail.com>

Simplify getActiveGatewayNodeName

This function enumerates the gateway nodes and spawns a pod to run
the 'hostname' command in search of the node whose name matches the
local Endpoint.Spec.Hostname. However we can simplify this by, instead,
searching for the "submariner-gateway" pod whose
"gateway.submariner.io/status" label is set to "active" and obtaining its
"gateway.submariner.io/node" label.

Signed-off-by: Tom Pantelis <tompantelis@gmail.com>

Improve diagnose firewall error output

These commands spawn a pod to run a 'tcpdump' command and
reports a failure if the output doesn't contain an expected
string. We should also report the pod output in case the
'tcpdump' command fails.

For the 'inter-cluster' command, the 'tcpdump' output is piped
to 'grep' to match the expected client message and stop when
found. However if an error occurs then the message isn't matched
so therefore the pod output is empty which isn't useful. Instead
use 'sed' instead of 'grep' which also outputs the non-matching
lines.

Signed-off-by: Tom Pantelis <tompantelis@gmail.com>

Fix issue with Azure g/w length

Azure machineset provider internally appends the infra name
to the public ip name. So the one added by submariner will be
reduntant. Also Submariner just need to enure that the name
it creates is unique when it spwans mutliple g/w node. So
a name the with zone and regions and subgw should be unique.
All the existing machineset will have infra name in it and
will not overlap with submariner.

Signed-off-by: Aswin Suryanarayanan <aswinsuryan@gmail.com>

Fix issue with Azure g/w length

Azure machineset provider internally appends the clustername
to the machine name. So it is not rquired to do it from
Submariner. Hence removing it.

issue.body:
These commands spawn a pod to run a `tcpdump` command and reports a failure if the output doesn't contain an expected string. We should also report the pod output in case the `tcpdump` command fails.

For the `inter-cluster` command, the `tcpdump` output is piped to `grep` to match the expected client message and stop when found. However if an error occurs then the message isn't matched and therefore the pod output is empty which isn't useful. Use `sed` instead of `grep` which also outputs the non-matching lines.

Improve error reporting for failed network pods (#432)

If the pod isn't scheduled, capture the reason and the pod status rather
than vaguely reporting that it timed out.

Signed-off-by: Tom Pantelis <tompantelis@gmail.com>

Give more permission for the diagnode pods

Some containers which run os like rhel/fedora runs tcpdump
as specific user id "72". So it needs pods to be privileged.
Also setting the runAsUser prevent the pods from starting with
random user id

* Make the diagnose pod a privileged
* Run the diagnose pod with userId 0

Signed-off-by: Aswin Suryanarayanan <aswinsuryan@gmail.com>

Simplify getActiveGatewayNodeName

This function enumerates the gateway nodes and spawns a pod to run
the 'hostname' command in search of the node whose name matches the
local Endpoint.Spec.Hostname. However we can simplify this by, instead,
searching for the "submariner-gateway" pod whose
"gateway.submariner.io/status" label is set to "active" and obtaining its
"gateway.submariner.io/node" label.

Signed-off-by: Tom Pantelis <tompantelis@gmail.com>

Improve diagnose firewall error output

These commands spawn a pod to run a 'tcpdump' command and
reports a failure if the output doesn't contain an expected
string. We should also report the pod output in case the
'tcpdump' command fails.

For the 'inter-cluster' command, the 'tcpdump' output is piped
to 'grep' to match the expected client message and stop when
found. However if an error occurs then the message isn't matched
so therefore the pod output is empty which isn't useful. Instead
use 'sed' instead of 'grep' which also outputs the non-matching
lines.

Signed-off-by: Tom Pantelis <tompantelis@gmail.com>

Fix issue with Azure g/w length

Azure machineset provider internally appends the infra name
to the public ip name. So the one added by submariner will be
reduntant. Also Submariner just need to enure that the name
it creates is unique when it spwans mutliple g/w node. So
a name the with zone and regions and subgw should be unique.
All the existing machineset will have infra name in it and
will not overlap with submariner.

Signed-off-by: Aswin Suryanarayanan <aswinsuryan@gmail.com>

Fix issue with Azure g/w length

Azure machineset provider internally appends the clustername
to the machine name. So it is not rquired to do it from
Submariner. Hence removing it.

Give more permission for the diagnode pods

Some containers which run os like rhel/fedora runs tcpdump
as specific user id "72". So it needs pods to be privileged.
Also setting the runAsUser prevent the pods from starting with
random user id

* Make the diagnose pod a privileged
* Run the diagnose pod with userId 0
